headline: US private job growth slows in August, grad unemployment: ADP
summary: Recent data suggests the labor market is softening, which could translate to an interest rate cut from the Federal Reserve at its September FOMC meeting. The US economy added 54,000 private sector jobs in August, according to the latest ADP employment report. missing the 68,000 jobs economists expected. Unemployment among recent graduates is on the rise, with the demographic making up the highest share of the overall unemployment rate since the 1980s. Yahoo Finance senior reporter Allie Canal outlines key takeaways from the labor data ahead of tomorrow's jobs report. headline: U.S. Trade Gap Rose in July
summary: The trade deficit in goods and services grew to $78.3 billion in July.  Total imports rose by $20 billion, or 5.9%, from June, according to the Commerce Department. Exports were roughly flat.   The result was close to forecasts by economists surveyed by The Wall Street Journal.

headline: ADP Report Shows Slowdown in Hiring
summary: Private sector hiring slowed sharply again last month, data from payroll processing group ADP indicated Thursday, suggesting ongoing weakness in the labor market that is likely to crystalize bets on near-term interest rate cuts from the Federal Reserve.  ADP’s National Employment Report showed 54,000 jobs were created in the private sector last month, down 49% from the upwardly-revised 106,000 tally in July.  “The year started with strong job growth, but that momentum has been whipsawed by uncertainty,” said ADP’s chief economist Nela Richardson.

headline: US private payrolls miss expectations in August
summary: WASHINGTON (Reuters) -U.S. private payrolls increased less than expected in August amid easing labor market conditions.  Private employment rose by 54,000 jobs last month after a slightly upwardly revised 106,000 increase in July, the ADP National Employment Report showed on Thursday.  The ADP report, jointly developed with the Stanford Digital Economy Lab, was published ahead of the more comprehensive employment report for August due to be released on Friday by the Labor Department's Bureau of Labor Statistics.
